Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll go with  make_move h2e2 —that is, moving the queen from h2 to e2.

This move delivers check to White’s king via the diagonal (since from e2 the queen immediately hits f1) and is protected by our rook on e8 along the e‐file. It forces White’s king to move to one of only a few squares (e1, f2, or g1), further limiting its already very restricted options. This keeps up the pressure on an opponent with almost no counterplay.

Your move!

I’ll play 1...Bd8–f6, moving the bishop from d8 to f6. 

This move delivers mate because after 1...Bd8f6 the white king on h8 is in check along the f6–g7–h8 diagonal. Its adjacent escape squares turn out to be covered: 

• g7 is attacked by the bishop now on f6,

• The white king’s escape square g1 is covered by the bishop on f2.
• The square h2 is controlled by the knight on f1.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, I noticed that the white side has only a lone king sitting on a1. Black’s queen is currently on e2. By playing Qe2–a2 (in UCI format: e2a2), black gives check along file a and also covers all the escape squares. Here's why Qe2a2 is mate:

• After Qe2–a2, the white king on a1 is immediately in check from the queen along the open a‑file.
• Its only possible escape squares from the corner are a2, b1, and b2.
  – a2 is occupied by the queen.
  – b1 is also covered diagonally by the queen (since a2–b1 is a one‐step diagonal).
  – b2 lies on rank 2, which is entirely controlled by the queen on a2.
• Additionally, if the king attempts to capture the queen on a2, the piece on a8 (the rook of black) on the a‑file would still be attacking a2, leaving the king in check.

Thus, Qe2a2 is a checkmating move.

I will now complete my turn with the move:

make_move e2a2

A useful plan for Black is to mobilize the rook and bring it to a more central and flexible role. Moving the rook from a8 along the 8th rank (for example, heading toward the center) is a natural way to improve its activity. In particular, moving the rook from a8 to d8 – that is, the move a8d8 – makes sense. Based on the board position—
• White king on b7;
• Black king on d6;
• Black pawn on h5;
• Black queen on a1–
it appears that any queen move that delivers an immediate check (for example, Qa1–a7) would allow White’s king to capture the queen on a7. In such an endgame (king and queen versus lone king), it’s crucial not to lose the queen by offering it for free, even if that check looks tempting.

A solid way to continue is a waiting move that continues to improve your position, while not giving White a chance to capture your queen. One natural candidate is to safely advance your h-pawn with h5–h4. That move is harmless‐yet it gains a tempo without risking your queen or king.

I'll now complete my turn with the move:

make_move h5h4
